    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <opener>Dear Sir</opener>
                <p>I forget how the epistolary debts are between us but for fear of error on my side
                    write to enquire how your health, and what acquisitions you make in your
                    collection. I have had your molluscs drawn; and wish much for one of those
                    long-legged sea insects to preserve it by a figure. When you and <persName ref="pe0247">Mr. Oglevie</persName> have settled the address of the box I am to
                    send, I will do my best to collect our ores, &amp;c. for you. I cannot get the
                    snake yet: it would make a good figure in <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0001">my Tour</title>
                    </bibl>, could it be procured but let me beg its
                    description. Have you yet got my icons of B<hi rend="superscript">r.</hi> A<hi rend="superscript">n.</hi>
                    <note type="editorial">Likely a reference to engravings in <bibl>Aylett Sammes, <title ref="bi0583">
                                <hi rend="italic">Britannia antiqua illustrata, or, The
                                    antiquities of ancient Britain, derived from the
                                    Phoenicians</hi>
                            </title>, (London: 1676)</bibl>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am Dear Sir <lb/>your faithful humble Servant</salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Tho. Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>

                <dateline>May 22<hi rend="superscript">nd.</hi> 1770.</dateline>
            </div>
